> z03` should exist. Actually, the inputs to gates don't change in a swap — only outputs. So the gate that originally was `t03 XOR c02 -> z03` still has inputs `t03` and `c02`, not `z05`. But now the carry wire is named `z05` (because the OR gate outputs `z05`), so we look for `XOR(t03, z05)` which doesn't exist. The original gate has inputs `t03` and `c02`.\n\nSo the carry value we're tracking is `z05`, but the next XOR gate still references `c02`. This means we can't find `XOR(t03, z05)`. We'd fall into the error recovery path. Let me trace through my algorithm for this case:\n\n1. At bit 3: partialSum = whatever xorGate outputs. carry = z05.\n2. Look for `XOR(partialSum, z05)` — doesn't exist.\n3. candidateA = find XOR gate with input z05 (excluding xorGate) — there IS a gate `t05 XOR c04 -> c02` (the original z05 gate that now outputs c02). But does this use z05 as input? No! The inputs are t05 and c04.\n4. candidateB = find XOR gate with input partialSum (excluding xorGate) — this would find the original `t03 XOR c02 -> z03` gate. Its other input is c02, which is what the carry should really be. But... c02 is the output of the swapped z05 gate, not the carry we're tracking.\n\nHmm, this is getting complicated. The issue is that when a carry wire is swapped with a distant z wire, the name `c02` no longer refers to the carry — it now refers to the z05 sum output. And `z05` now refers to the carry.\n\nActually wait. Let me reconsider. In a swap of c02 <-> z05:\n- The gate that was `a02 OR b02 -> c02` now has `a02 OR b02 -> z05` (output changed to z05)\n- The gate that was `t05 XOR c04 -> z05` now has `t05 XOR c04 -> c02` (output changed to c02)\n- All other gates are unchanged — their inputs still reference the original wire names.\n\nSo the gate `t03 XOR c02 -> z03` still has inputs t03 and c02. But c02 now comes from `t05 XOR c04` (the wrong value). The correct carry for bit 3 is z05 (which comes from `a02 OR b02`).\n\nWhen my algorithm processes bit 3:\n- carry